p.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15023/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15023/canvas/1/67a1b50c-2210-4313-a126-929a7fa182b7","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-07-01T18:51:16.618Z","creator":"Ada ","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>As Reynolds’s confesses to Cyril that he feels like he’s “made a terrible mistake” by marrying Alma, he adopts a pose as if praying. In a film largely devoid of religious imagery and themes, this moment feels significant, as Reynolds is brought low and makes an appeal not to any sort of higher power but to his sister, on whom he has depended all his life.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-15023/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:726.7192476114649,129.25631966560508,462.0874800955414,826.7137738853503"}}}]}]}]}